        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Correlator Setup: Our science goal requires 4 spectral windows in order to simultaneously observe the three deuterated species: N2D+, DCN and DCO+, along with a wide continuum (TDM) window for phase calibration and dust continuum emission.  We expect the spectral lines to be quite narrow (&lt;2 km/s) with features below 0.1 km/s.  We therefore choose the narrowest FDM window, which provides 0.04 km/s resolution (a factor of two improvement on recent studies by Tan et al. 2013 with ALMA and by Pineda &amp; Teixeria 2013 with APEX).  The frequency of our continuum spectral window is chosen to avoid any strong lines (interstellar or atmospheric).

Sensitivity:  We focus our sensitivity estimates on N2D+, as we expect this to be the best tracer of the cold dense gas (of these three deuterated species; e.g. Tan et al. 2013, Caselli et al. 2002).  Because the deuteration fraction of MM2 is unknown, we base our sensitivity estimates on those sources in the literature that come closest to being analogs for MM2.  Tan et al. (2013) observed N2D+(3-2), DCO+(3-2) and DCN(3-2) in their ALMA Cycle 0 study of massive cores (see also discussion in Science Case) with ~2.3” resolution; of their six cores, five have N2D+ peak brightness temperatures of &gt; ~0.25 K.  We expect the size scale of the N2D+ emission from MM2 to be well-matched to the requested ALMA beam (see below).  Our sensitivity requirement is based on detecting the N2D+ line in MM2, a remarkably line-free yet massive core, down to a 5-sigma peak strength of 0.25K (requiring 0.05K rms) when binned to 0.08 km/s channels.  This will provide a factor of 45 better sensitivity than the current SMA upper limit and will either detect the line or deliver a severe constraint on the gas abundance and deuteration history of this object.




Imaging Requirements: Our goal is to detect line emission from MM2.  The deconvolved size of MM2, as measured from our SMA continuum images, ranges from ~0.45” to ~ 1.2” in our highest/lowest resolution SMA data.  (Quoted sizescales are the geometric mean of the deconvolved source size, measured from 2D Gaussian fitting in the image plane.)  Our highest (0.46”) and lowest (2.4”) resolution SMA data were taken with the same 1.3 mm tuning, so the measured continuum flux densities can be compared directly (e.g. without the need to scale by a spectral index).  The high-resolution image recovers only ~ 44% of the flux, indicating that a significant amount of mass is extended on ~ arcsecond scales.  We thus expect the size of the N2D+ emission to be ~1” to 1.5”.   

Therefore, we require an angular resolution of 1.5” in order to provide a good match to the size of the object (and so avoid beam dilution) while achieving good brightness temperature sensitivity.  The requested resolution is also necessary to fully isolate emission from MM2 from possible emission from other (proto)cluster members (both known sources and fainter neighbors that may be newly-detected by ALMA).  At a distance of 3.8 kpc, the beam corresponds to ~5700 AU, which is comfortably below the typical size scale of separation between massive protostars (~10,000 AU).

A single pointing easily covers the area of interest; importantly, MM1 will also be included within the primary beam.  Because MM2 is so unusual, the ability to do a comparative study with another core in the same protocluster is particularly useful (as we have seen in analyzing our SMA data).  The largest angular scale is at most 8”, which is recoverable in the single configuration that can deliver the resolution.

Calibration: We do not require any unusual calibration.

Scheduling constraints: none</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
