        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Correlator Setup: Our science goal requires 1 FDM spectral window to measure N2H+(3-2).  We use 3 additional TDM windows for phase calibration and to get a sensitive continuum image to compare with the Band 6 continuum image from the other science goal. We expect the spectral line to be quite narrow (&lt; 2.5 km/s, and potentially 1 km/s or less; e.g. Fontani et al. 2006 A&amp;A, 460, 709), with features below 0.1 km/s.  We therefore choose the narrowest FDM window, which provides 0.038 km/s resolution, and spectral averaging factor of 2 to reduce the data rate somewhat.

Sensitivity: Our sensitivity requirement is based on detecting the N2H+(3-2) line in this remarkably line-free yet massive core, down to a 5-sigma peak strength of 0.5K (requiring 0.1K rms) at 0.061 MHz resolution (0.66 km/s).  This will provide a factor of 35 better sensitivity than the current
SMA upper limit and will either detect the line or
deliver a severe constraint on the gas abundance.

The low abundance limit for N2H+ derived from our SMA N2H+(3-2) observations (&lt;10^-13; see description in Science Case) is driven in large part by the very high H2 column density, N(H2), estimated from the dust continuum emission.  Time-dependent gas-grain models (Fig. 2, Science Case) indicate that above densities of ~1e8 cm^-3, CO will be depleted on timescales of years, and N2H+ will quickly approach an abundance of ~10^-9, as long as the temperature is above ~17 K (the N2 freeze-out temperature).  As shown in Figure 2, lower N2H+ abundances (between ~10^-11 and 10^-13) are expected for T&lt;17 K, and at higher densities (compared to 10^-9 cm^-3, shown in Fig. 2) the N2H+ abundance is further depressed.

As a benchmark sensitivity, for an N2H+ abundance of 10^-10 (typical of low-mass prestellar cores), RADEX modeling predicts line brightness temperatures of ~12-27 K for T_kin in the range of 12-40 K, for column and number densities that yield the mass inferred from the dust emission.

The low N2H+ abundance limit calculated from the SMA data, when compared to the chemical models, suggests that either (1) one or more of the assumptions going into the SMA abundance estimate is incorrect (for example, the assumed line width, or the dust temperature that enters into the N(H2) estimate), or (2) MM2 is indeed so cold (at the low end of its allowed temperature range) that the gas-phase N2H+ abundance is depressed due to (partial) freeze out.  The proposed ALMA observations, with their vastly improved sensitivity, will establish which scenario is correct.  Importantly, our continuum science goal will also improve our estimates of the N(H2) column density based on improved imaging of the dust continuum emission and sufficient S/N to constrain radiative transfer models.  

 Imaging Requirements: The imaging requirements are the same as those for the N2D+ science goal: our goal is to detect line emission from MM2.  We expect the size of the N2H+ emission to be ~1” to 1.5” and therefore require an angular resolution of 1.5” in order to provide a good match to the size of the object (and so avoid beam dilution) while achieving good brightness temperature sensitivity.  The requested resolution is also necessary to fully isolate emission from MM2 from possible emission from other (proto)cluster members (both known sources and fainter neighbors that may be newly-detected by ALMA).  At a distance of 3.8 kpc, the beam corresponds to ~5700 AU, which is comfortably below the typical size scale of separation between massive protostars (~10,000 AU).

A single pointing easily covers the area of interest; importantly, MM1 will also be included within the primary beam.  Because MM2 is so unusual, the ability to do a comparative study with another core in the same protocluster is particularly useful (as we have seen in analyzing our SMA data).  The largest angular scale is at most 8”, which is recoverable in the single configuration that can deliver the resolution.</prj:justificationText>
