        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging: The goal is to measure the density
profile by observing the dust continuum emission
over a broad range of angular scales (from 0.2 to
10 arcsec).  This requires two 12m configurations
plus the ACA.

Sensitivity: We expect the multi-configuration
image to have a synthesized beam more like 0.3
arcseconds due to the large number of short
spacings.  Based on the peak intensity of the
source in our existing SMA images with a 0.4"
beam, we expect the peak continuum emission in the
multi-configuration ALMA image to be about 50 mJy.
In order to measure the density profile across a
factor of 33 in diameter (from the beamsize out to
10 arcseconds), we require a peak signal to noise
of 1000.  This yields a requested rms of 0.05
mJy. This requires only 7 minutes on-source with
the 12m array.  The total time request (2.0 hr) is
dominated by the time for calibration, overhead
and ACA observations.

Correlator setup: The is a purely continuum
project using the default tuning for Band 6.

Calibration: We do not require any unusual
calibration.

Scheduling contraints: none

Data rate: This all-TDM experiment has a low data
rate.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
